                </div>

                <div class="span8">
                  <h2>
                    <a
                      href="/untyping/2006/01/21/untyped-hosting/"
                      rel="bookmark"
                      title="Permanent Link to Untyped hosting?"
                      >Untyped hosting?</a
                    >
                  </h2>

                  <div class="entry">
                    <p>
                      <em
                        >In chatting with¬†<a
                          href="http://www.crypticscriber.com/">Nick</a
                        >¬†about hosting, I began to realize how complex the ISP
                        game can be. These are some thoughts, all provide
                        starting points for further brainstorming and
                        discussion.</em
                      >
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      We‚Äôre building our new machine for ourselves, make no
                      mistake. We took this route because it looked cost
                      effective for the needs we had for ourselves. However, we
                      can, in theory, provide services to others as well‚Äîas our
                      server is more than capable of supporting more than just
                      untyped.
                    </p>
                    <p>But what services would we offer, and at what cost?</p>
                    <p>
                      We currently run Apache, Exim/Courier, Postgres and MySQL,
                      Subversion‚Ä¶ in general, a full assortment of services that
                      users might want to make use of. Through judicious use of
                      LDAP, we‚Äôre hoping to expose some of these services
                      (email, WWW) without needing to provide full (shell)
                      accounts on the server. Likewise, we‚Äôre planning and
                      building scripts to automate many of our maintenance tasks
                      on the machine; we‚Äôre stopping short of CPanel, however.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      So if we have the means to support other users, why would
                      I be hesitant? Because we are not an ISP. We are people
                      who enjoy making software. Our machine is like our
                      workbench‚Äîit provides the essential services we need to
                      make that software. Therefore, we have no interest in
                      trying to compete with your run-of-the-mill ISPs‚Ä¶ you can
                      get a $5/month web account anywhere. So what kind of
                      hosting will we provide?
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      At the least, I imagine we might offer hosting for ‚Äúodd‚Äù
                      servers and languages. By ‚Äúodd‚Äù, I mean ‚Äúanything not
                      Apache.‚Äù For example, we know that there might be some
                      interest in the PLT Scheme; likewise, I imagine that
                      allowing servers written in Erlang may be of interest as
                      well. Beyond that‚Ä¶ how much bandwidth can someone expect
                      to get hosting with us? Do we provide backup services?
                      What kind of quota does a user‚Äôs account come with? What
                      kind of response time to user requests are we going to try
                      and make good on?
                    </p>
                    <h3>Bandwidth</h3>
                    <p>
                      We will probably have 50GB of traffic per month in our
                      colo agreement. We will be charged beyond that as per
                      Bytemark‚Äôs policies. Therefore, I could simply pass on
                      costs to clients. Really, though, we‚Äôre not prepared to
                      deal with the administrative overhead of billing clients
                      for bandwidth, etc.; we‚Äôll barely be in a position to
                      administer billing for basic services. Again, we‚Äôre back
                      to the mantra ‚Äúwe are not an ISP.‚Äù
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      We‚Äôll have bandwidth accounting in place; how you charge
                      for bandwidth, I don‚Äôt know. Just having to administer
                      this takes time, and time is money (‚ÄúWe are not an ISP‚Ä¶‚Äù).
                      Perhaps there‚Äôs a simple way to handle this‚Ä¶ perhaps not.
                      I need to think more on this one; insights are welcome.
                    </p>
                    <h3>Backup</h3>
                    <p>
                      Backup is expensive. It takes careful scripting on the
                      host, regular movement of data from the server to a remote
                      site (see ‚ÄúBandwidth,‚Äù above), and it takes time to
                      archive that to some kind of storage media. I don‚Äôt have a
                      tape jukebox anywhere near the server, nor can I afford
                      one (‚ÄúWe are not an ISP‚Äù ). Therefore, backup is an issue
                      of me having a second machine that runs a cron job, and
                      regularly pulls backups off the server. Then, I‚Äôll have to
                      manually burn DVDs and/or make digital tapes archives of
                      that data. There are time and media costs involved in this
                      that are non-trivial.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      Backup is something that typically is not offered with a
                      shell account, period. Taking a look at¬†<a
                        href="http://www.mythic-beasts.com/pricelist.html"
                        >Mythic Beasts</a
                      >, their shell accounts start at ¬£15 per quarter, they
                      offer 200MB of disk space, and there is no mention of
                      backup. I found some backup services while investigating
                      storage (below), and they charge a lot per month for 1GB
                      of backup (¬£25). This says to me that most hosting
                      facilities assume the following:
                    </p>
                    <ul>
                      <li>You backup your own data</li>
                      <li>If the server dies, you‚Äôre on your own</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>
                      I‚Äôm not committed to either route at this point, but it‚Äôs
                      clear that I should charge money for backup services. I‚Äôm
                      willing to spend my time to guarantee my own data‚Äôs
                      safety, but I‚Äôm not willing to do that for others, for
                      free.
                    </p>
                    <h3>Storage</h3>
                    <p>
                      What kind of quotas should we provide users? What can I
                      get shopping around the internet?
                    </p>
                    <p>&nbsp;</p>
                    <p></p>
                    <center>
                      &nbsp;
                      <table width="80%">
                        <tbody>
                          <tr>
                            <td><strong>Site</strong></td>
                            <td><strong>Capacity</strong></td>
                            <td><strong>Monthly</strong></td>
                          </tr>
                          <tr>
                            <td>
