                            <td>1GB</td>
                            <td>¬£1.70</td>
                          </tr>
                          <tr>
                            <td><a href="http://www.box.net/">box.net</a></td>
                            <td>5GB</td>
                            <td>¬£4.50</td>
                          </tr>
                          <tr>
                            <td>
                              <a href="http://www.storegate.com/"
                                >storegate.com</a
                              >
                            </td>
                            <td>1GB</td>
                            <td>¬£5.00</td>
                          </tr>
                          <tr>
                            <td>
                              <a href="http://www.xdrive.com/">xdrive.com</a>
                            </td>
                            <td>5GB</td>
                            <td>¬£5.60</td>
                          </tr>
                          <tr>
                            <td>
                              <a href="http://www.ibackup.com/">ibackup.com</a>
                            </td>
                            <td>5GB</td>
                            <td>¬£5.60</td>
                          </tr>
                          <tr>
                            <td>
                              <a href="http://www.datafort.co.uk/"
                                >www.datafort.co.uk</a
                              >
                            </td>
                            <td>1GB (compressed)</td>
                            <td>¬£25</td>
                          </tr>
                        </tbody>
                      </table>
                      <p>&nbsp;</p>
                      <p></p>
                    </center>
                    &nbsp;
                    <p>
                      <a
                        href="http://www.epinions.com/webs-Web_Services-All-Online_Storage"
                        >Epinions</a
                      >¬†has more commentary on online storage than I care to
                      duplicate here. I myself have a 1GB¬†<a
                        href="http://www.box.net/">Box.net</a
                      >¬†account, and am quite pleased with it‚Äîtheir pricing is
                      competitive, and the interface to the site, as well as
                      features (instant photo albums, passwords, RSS feeds) are
                      great.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      Point being? If I‚Äôm going to offer space, I have to charge
                      at least ¬£1.75/GB; and since we‚Äôre not really in this
                      market space to compete, I‚Äôd probably have to charge more
                      than that (due to the administrative overheads, and
                      limited resources on our own machine). Furthermore, that‚Äôs
                      assuming it‚Äôs a gigabyte of¬†<em>unarchived storage</em>.
                      It looks like sites that actually offer backup of a
                      gigabyte of data charge around ¬£25/month for a gigabyte of
                      content that gets archived monthly. This doesn‚Äôt surprise
                      me in the least‚Äîoffering security is an expensive
                      proposition, both in terms of tools and in terms of time.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      Again, comparing,¬†<a
                        href="http://www.mythic-beasts.com/pricelist.html"
                        >Mythic Beasts</a
                      >¬†charge ¬£30 per month for a ‚Äúdeveloper‚Äù account with 1GB
                      of disk (no backup). The reality is (because we‚Äôre not an
                      ISP), we only have one server, with limited disk space. I
                      can resell storage from Bytemark, which eases the stress
                      on my own disks‚Ä¶ but as can be seen, having active disk
                      space that you can serve out to the world costs money.
                    </p>
                    <h3>Administration</h3>
                    <p>
                      All these services take time to administer. Yes, we have
                      to do it for ourselves‚Ä¶ but it‚Äôs another thing entirely to
                      have customers who want guarantees, and support when
                      things go wrong (regardless of whether it is at our end or
                      their end). What does administration cost? I can look at
                      other ISPs and see what they charge for adding a
                      subdomain, or configuring databases, or any of a host of
                      things‚Ä¶ and I don‚Äôt want to get trapped in a situation
                      where we offer to do these things ‚Äúfor free,‚Äù and end up
                      playing sysadmin to a bunch of customers without any
                      recompense.
                    </p>
                    <p>Again, this is a tough one.</p>
                    <h3>In Conclusion‚Ä¶ or, something like that</h3>
                    <p>
                      This isn‚Äôt necessarily the kind of laundry a small
                      business should air in public. Typically, this is the kind
                      of uncertainty that would be kept private, resolved
                      off-line, and then published to the world as policy.
                      However, these are probably the kind of questions that
                      others have wrestled with in their time, and it‚Äôs possible
                      someone who reads untyping may have some insights into
                      these issues that we don‚Äôt have. Given that we only have
                      one machine (‚ÄúWe are not an ISP‚Äù), it may be that we
                      should avoid hosting altogether. Or perhaps we can come up
                      with some reasonable terms of service and pricing
                      structures that reflect the quality and nature of services
                      we will offer. Who knows? Either way, they‚Äôre challenging
                      questions.
                    </p>
                  </div>

